{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01AxdvexkdUcr5TfSMMi1ahp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Looking at this git-reading CLI tool, I need to evaluate what each behavior requires to catch real failures.\n\n**Critical insight**: All 5 behaviors depend on how the tool interfaces with actual git repositories and parses real git output. The failure boundaries are not in isolated logic—they're at the system boundary where git commands are executed and their output is processed.\n\nLet me work through each:\n\n**Behavior 1 (renamed files)**: Real git uses specific output formats to distinguish renames from add+delete (e.g., `R100  old.txt -> new.txt` in `--name-status` output). A mock could pass with a simplified structure, but the real failure happens when the tool misparses git's actual output format.\n\n**Behavior 2 (binary files)**: Git outputs binary diffs differently (`Binary files ... differ`). The tool must handle this exact format without crashing. A mock of pre-parsed data would hide parsing failures.\n\n**Behavior 3 (no commits)**: Git returns a specific error when HEAD doesn't exist. The tool must catch and handle it. A mock could simulate any error; catching the real one requires real git state.\n\n**Behavior 4 (counts match)**: This is the core correctness requirement. You must verify against a real repository with known change history—no mock can substitute for this.\n\n**Behavior 5 (staged vs unstaged)**: The tool's behavior must be consistent regardless of whether you test `git diff` (unstaged) or `git diff --cached` (staged). Real git state is essential.\n\nAll require **System level** as the most reliable minimum, with some probability that Integration could work if the tool has a clean abstraction layer around git."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13428,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral